      "text": "Every company should start making clarity on the specific reason why they need or want to scale. Different teams, different parts of the organisation, different people and different leaders will likely have different reasons. Each of them will drive their local effort to scale starting from their own reasons. All these local reasons to scale will contribute to the emergence of an overall reason to scale for the whole organisation. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "f7549c0081729a75",
      "text": "# Comments from SPA 2021\n\nSmall experiments can be run to test that scaling is actually moving the needle in the direction of solving the problems it was supposed to solve. So it should start clarifying what need or problem the organisation is trying to solve.\n  \nThere will be a delay between any change made and its impact, with a potential decrease in productivity before things start to go better, with this in mind the experiments should be designed to be small and provide answers in a short time.  \n  \nThe experimentation itself goes through a learning process.\n  \nExamples of anticipatory signs that scaling may soon become beneficial include a growing customer base approaching the limits of the system capability, the product expansion in areas where more skills and expertise are needed, a growing gap between ideas and their delivery, declining quality because teams are too busy in fulfilling the growing demand.\n"
